  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Multisectoral response to storm victims in  Maniema</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">An unrestricted cash intervention is appropriate in the affected area to cover the needs of food (for 15 days), NFIs and shelter and hygiene items, and health especially for the injured people. The local market in the area remains accessible and has availability of items. Therefore, communities will be able  to acquire key food, shelter and NFI items. The cash grants will enable recipients to repair their shelters damaged by the heavy rains and strong winds, procure essential household items, buy food stock or seeds and to meet other needs of the household like health and education. This will allow them to be sheltered from the weather, reduce the likelihood of getting sick, the spread of coronavirus and provide for their immediate needs which will allow them to lead a dignified and secure life again. A lump sum will be granted to the injured to help pay for their medical care.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Each household will receive &#xA3; 170 respectively for disaster victims and &#xA3;75 for host households. These amounts are within the range of the household basket values calculated by the Cash Working Group in eastern DRC. This is preferred as it ensures that households can spend the cash on what they most need. Given that the transfers are digital, it minimises the risk of theft and diversion and is a convenient and fast way to disperse funds to the disaster-affected.</narrative>
  </description>
